CATER 155499, FACET Magnet Q0FF: supply does not regulate well.
text: Rack FKG20-40, Level 20, Magnet Q0FF: tried local control. Supply comes up with volts and amps out, but ACR states it doesn't regulate well. Swapped power plug from Q0FF to Q5FF. Same fault on local control board as seen last week: power supply fault, no system ready. De-energized rack from feed breaker panel. Removed ckt breaker panel cover at top of rack. Checked all line and load side connections on all breakers in panel. Discovered the L3 on line side of the 2 breakers for Q0FF + Q5FF was mildly loose. Approx. 2 full turns to make it tight. Believe this is original problem. Re-energized all rack 40 supplies. It appears problem with input voltage sag is gone. CATER ready to close. --chw, sj

title: Lessons from Ryan about how to use LI20 screens:
text: -To move screens in, click on ladder and send to YAG. The motor position may not be quite right. You'll have to adjust manually -On the PYDM All Cameras button (mint green): if there's no green light/screen is not updating, try rebooting. This can take several minutes.

Coherent 1 Follow Up
text: Looking into reports that Coherent 1 was reporting an alarm status, found that the calibration, when last run, wasn't very good, and the laser was registering a large number of bucket jumps (around 11k and counting when I looked at it). Calibration error was reported on the order of 10 ns. I also found that the output time measurement was jittering a large amount. I resent trigger thresholds and time interval counter settings to make sure that it hadn't just booted with an incorrect configuration, but the system still seems to be moving a fair amount, so I suspect that the regen diode alignment might be off. It still seems to have periods of stability and periods of jumping, so the system is not yet operating correctly. Until laser gets a chance to look at the alignment, expect to still get intermittent alarms as the recorded jitter exceeds thresholds. However, as long as it doesn't drift too much from 'center', the laser output itself should be stable and the locker won't erroneously try to correct on this output. However, if ops sees an increase in bucket corrects (OSC:LR20:20:FS_CORRECTION_CNT), then this should be escalated.

title: Modulator 24-4: core bias current and voltage measurements vs. PLC touch panel readings
text: Modulator 24-4: core bias current and voltage measurements vs. PLC touch panel readings below. PLC touch panel readings: 15.0 ADC 5.9x VDC Amprobe DC clamp-on ammeter and Fluke DMM for volt meter: 15.8 ADC 6.0x VDC The two sets of measurements are close enough to indicate the core bias supply (and PLC controller) are working OK. Beings the voltage measurement is higher (should be around 4.4 VDC), the resistance of the core bias winding (and interconnecting wiring) is higher than normal. Something may be failing in the klystron tank. When the voltage, as indicated by the PLC touch panel gets above 6.0 VDC, the current reading becomes erratic because the PLC can no longer regulate because the AC controller is phased forward all the way. Did this measurements with technicians. p.erebia, c.herr, r.matausch, p.stiles
